{"award_age":34.0,"bio_image":"full\/ca1ed8626711354496ab27a3d68e66452c3ce5dd.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1928-04-06T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/8\/8b\/James_D_Watson.jpg\/250px-James_D_Watson.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_D._Watson","mini_bio":"<p><b>James Dewey Watson<\/b> (born April 6, 1928) is an American <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Molecular_biology\" title=\"Molecular biology\">molecular biologist<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Genetics\" title=\"Genetics\">geneticist<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Zoologist\" title=\"Zoologist\" class=\"mw-redirect\">zoologist<\/a>, best known as one of the co-discoverers of the structure of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/DNA\" title=\"DNA\">DNA<\/a> in 1953 with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_Crick\" title=\"Francis Crick\">Francis Crick<\/a>. Watson, Crick, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Maurice_Wilkins\" title=\"Maurice Wilkins\">Maurice Wilkins<\/a> were awarded the 1962 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> \"for their discoveries concerning the molecular structure of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nucleic_acid\" title=\"Nucleic acid\">nucleic acids<\/a> and its significance for information transfer in living material\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-The_Nobel_Foundation_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_D._Watson#cite_note-The_Nobel_Foundation-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>After studies at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Chicago\" title=\"University of Chicago\">University of Chicago<\/a> (B.S., 1947) and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Indiana_University\" title=\"Indiana University\">Indiana University<\/a> (Ph.D., 1950), Watson did postdoctoral research to absorb chemistry with the biochemist Herman Kalckar in Copenhagen. Watson next worked at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Cambridge\" title=\"University of Cambridge\">University of Cambridge<\/a>'s <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cavendish_Laboratory\" title=\"Cavendish Laboratory\">Cavendish Laboratory<\/a> in England, where he first met his future collaborator and friend <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_Crick\" title=\"Francis Crick\">Francis Crick<\/a>.<\/p><p>From 1956 to 1976, Watson was on the faculty of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Harvard_University\" title=\"Harvard University\">Harvard University<\/a> Biology Department, promoting research in molecular biology.<sup id=\"cite_ref-The_Nobel_Foundation_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_D._Watson#cite_note-The_Nobel_Foundation-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> From 1968 he served as director of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cold_Spring_Harbor_Laboratory\" title=\"Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory\">Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory<\/a> (CSHL) on <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Long_Island,_New_York\" title=\"Long Island, New York\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Long Island, New York<\/a>, greatly expanding its level of funding and research. At CSHL, he shifted his research emphasis to the study of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cancer\" title=\"Cancer\">cancer<\/a>, along with making it a world leading research center in molecular biology. In 1994, he started as president and served for 10 years. He was then appointed chancellor, serving until 2007 <sup id=\"cite_ref-CSHL_bio_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_D._Watson#cite_note-CSHL_bio-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> when he resigned his position after making controversial comments claiming a link between intelligence and geographical ancestry.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_D._Watson#cite_note-7\"><span>[<\/span>7<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Independent_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_D._Watson#cite_note-Independent-8\"><span>[<\/span>8<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-cshl.edu_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_D._Watson#cite_note-cshl.edu-9\"><span>[<\/span>9<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-LATimes_10-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_D._Watson#cite_note-LATimes-10\"><span>[<\/span>10<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Resign_11-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_D._Watson#cite_note-Resign-11\"><span>[<\/span>11<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> Between 1988 and 1992, Watson was associated with the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/National_Institutes_of_Health\" title=\"National Institutes of Health\">National Institutes of Health<\/a>, helping to establish the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Human_Genome_Project\" title=\"Human Genome Project\">Human Genome Project<\/a>.<\/p><p>Watson has written many science books, including the textbook <i>Molecular Biology of the Gene<\/i><sup id=\"cite_ref-MBOTG_12-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_D._Watson#cite_note-MBOTG-12\"><span>[<\/span>12<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> (1965) and his bestselling book <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/The_Double_Helix\" title=\"The Double Helix\">The Double Helix<\/a><\/i><sup id=\"cite_ref-DH_13-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_D._Watson#cite_note-DH-13\"><span>[<\/span>13<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> (1968) about the DNA structure discovery, reissued in a new edition in 2012 - <i>The Annotated and Illustrated Double Helix<\/i> edited by Alex Gann and Jan Witkowski.<sup id=\"cite_ref-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_D._Watson#cite_note-14\"><span>[<\/span>14<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"James D. Watson","place_of_birth":"Chicago ,  Illinois ,  United States","place_of_death":null,"text":"James D. Watson , Physiology or Medicine, 1962","year":1962.0}